{"type":"message","id":"10183cc6","parentId":"8c097d7b","timestamp":"2026-05-01T15:36:36.545Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Sections 7, 8, and 9 are substantial (178, 257, 256 lines). Let me read all three to understand what's there and what needs to be completed.","thinkingSignature":"091cef29f0f8b9056af98759da01e33ab82bc0d3286aac06fa54bd58ab3474f0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0kle4ngrzv9r_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/OpenClaw/OpenClaw-Guide-By-Bobby/Section-7-Your-First-Automation.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0kle4ngrzv9r_2","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/OpenClaw/OpenClaw-Guide-By-Bobby/Section-8-Real-World-Workflows.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0kle4ngrzv9r_3","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/OpenClaw/OpenClaw-Guide-By-Bobby/Section-9-Advanced-Techniques.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":251,"output":190,"cacheRead":53184,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":53625,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777649792942,"responseId":"0643fb816e2b4db53d20fea1f2644f25"}}
{"type":"message","id":"acbacafb","parentId":"10183cc6","timestamp":"2026-05-01T15:36:36.719Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_0kle4ngrzv9r_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# OpenClaw Guide by Bobby G.\n\n*A practical, real-world guide to OpenClaw — written by someone who uses it daily.*\n\n---\n\n## Section 7: Your First Automation — The Morning Brief Skill\n\nThis is where it gets real. I'm going to show you how to build and install your first automation — the **Morning Brief skill**. This is the one I use every single day to start my morning right. I wake up, and before I'm even out of bed, everything I need to know is already there.\n\nOnce you see how powerful this is — something that runs automatically, every day, without you doing anything — you'll start seeing all kinds of other things you can build.\n\n---\n\n### What Does the Morning Brief Actually Do?\n\nEvery morning at 5:30 AM, my OpenClaw sends me a full briefing via Telegram. It includes:\n\n- **Today's weather** — current temperature, what it feels like, the high and low, wind, humidity, UV index, rain chance. Plus an hour-by-hour breakdown so I know what to wear and when to go outside.\n- **A Bible verse with personal motivation** — something relevant to what's on my calendar or what's coming up in my life that day. Not just a random verse — one that actually speaks to my situation.\n- **My calendar for the next 7 days** — everything I have coming up, who's involved, what time. Plus any bills that are due soon so I never miss a payment.\n- **Any reminders I have set** — anything incomplete in my reminders list, right there in the briefing.\n- **Suggestions for how I can help today** — seven specific, actionable things I could do that day based on what's on my plate.\n\nAll of this happens before I'm even out of bed. No checking apps, no scrolling, no checking things manually. I wake up informed and ready to go.\n\n---\n\n### Why Start With the Morning Brief?\n\nThe Morning Brief is a perfect first automation for three reasons:\n\n**1. It teaches you how skills work.** You build a skill once, set it to run on a schedule, and it runs automatically. That's the core pattern for almost everything in OpenClaw. Morning Brief teaches you this pattern in a practical, high-value way.\n\n**2. It's something you'll use every day.** The value is immediate and obvious. You wake up, see the briefing, and you're already getting use out of what you built. That positive feedback loop keeps you motivated to build more.\n\n**3. It shows you the power of automations.** Once you see something happen automatically — without you doing anything — you start thinking about what else could run on its own. That's the mindset shift that makes OpenClaw really powerful.\n\n---\n\n### Part 1: What is a Skill? (Quick Recap)\n\nA skill is a set of instructions that tells your OpenClaw how to do something — and how to do it the same way every time. You build it once, it works forever.\n\nInstead of telling my OpenClaw every morning \"give me the weather, my calendar, and a Bible verse,\" I built a skill that already knows all of that. Now it runs on its own. I don't have to ask. I don't have to remind it. It just happens because I set it up once.\n\nThe Morning Brief skill is a perfect first automation because it shows you the power of building something once and letting it run automatically.\n\n---\n\n### Part 2: What Goes Into the Morning Brief?\n\nHere's the actual breakdown of what my morning brief includes every day:\n\n**Header Section**\n- The day, date, and a greeting\n- \"Here's what we've got going on for today\" to set the tone\n\n**Weather**\n- Current temperature and feels-like\n- High/low for the day\n- Wind speed, humidity, UV index, rain chance\n- Hour-by-hour breakdown for 9 AM, 12 PM, 3 PM, 6 PM, 9 PM\n- One-sentence verdict on what the day is like overall\n\n**Bible Verse**\n- The verse text\n- The reference and version\n- A personalized motivation section that ties the verse to what's actually on my calendar or in my life that day\n\n**Calendar**\n- 7-day view of everything coming up\n- Events with times\n- Bills that are due soon (with amounts and due dates)\n- A \"based on your schedule\" insight at the bottom\n\n**Reminders**\n- Any incomplete reminders from my list\n- If nothing's pending, it says \"None\" — no empty section clutter\n\n**Suggestions**\n- Seven actionable things I could do that day\n- Specific and tied to actual items from the briefing\n- Things I can actively do, not just generic ideas\n\nEach section has a specific format. That consistency is what makes it reliable. Every morning, I know exactly where to look and what the format will be.\n\n---\n\n### Part 3: Install the Morning Brief Skill\n\nHere's how to get it running on your setup:\n\n**Step 1: Copy the skill file**\nThe skill template is included in the guide folder as `Morning-Brief-Skill-Template.md`. Copy it to your OpenClaw skills directory. (I'll include the exact path in the final guide.)\n\n**Step 2: Customize it for your information**\nThe skill comes with my specifics — my location (Knoxville, 37919), my email address, my calendar name. You'll need to swap those out for your own.\n\nHere's what to change:\n- **Location zip code** — swap `37919` for your zip code (weather comes from your zip code)\n- **Email account** — swap `rtg.bobby@gmail.com` for your email\n- **Calendar name** — swap `Family Calendar` for whatever your calendar is actually called in iCloud\n- **Telegram chat ID** — swap `8212808444` for your actual Telegram chat ID (this is how it knows where to send the message)\n\n**Step 3: Set up the cron job**\nOnce the skill is installed, you set up a **cron job** that tells OpenClaw to run the skill at a specific time every day. For me, it's 5:30 AM. For you, it could be whatever time works best for your morning routine.\n\nThe cron job is what makes it automatic. Once it's set up, the skill runs whether you're awake, asleep, or not even at your computer. You set it once, it works forever.\n\n**Step 4: Test it**\nBefore you rely on it, test it. Run the skill manually a few times to make sure it's pulling the right data and formatting everything correctly. Once it's working, you're done. You never have to think about it again.\n\n---\n\n### Part 4: Customize It For You\n\nThat's the whole point. This isn't a locked-in system — it's a template. You can make it work for you.\n\n**Want to add a section?** Maybe you want your morning brief to include your to-do list, or your top three emails, or your fitness goals for the day. Add it.\n\n**Want to remove a section?** If you don't care about the Bible verse, take it out. If you don't want reminders in your brief, remove it. You're building this for yourself.\n\n**Want to change the format?** The way the weather is laid out, the order of sections, the emojis used — all of it is customizable. Once you have the template working, you can tweak anything you want.\n\n**Want to change what the suggestions are?** Right now my suggestions are specific to things in the briefing. You could change the logic to prioritize different things — whatever matters most to you.\n\nSkills are customizable because they're just files with instructions in them. You own them, you can edit them, you can change them whenever you want. You're not stuck with what someone else built.\n\n---\n\n### Part 5: What If You Want to Tweak It Later?\n\nYes. That's the whole point.\n\nThe first version you build won't be perfect. You'll use it for a week, realize you don't actually look at one section, and decide to remove it. Or you realize the weather format is taking up too much space. Or you want to add a new section for your podcast notes.\n\nThat's not a problem — that's the process. Your morning brief will evolve as you use it and discover what you actually need. The template is a starting point, not a final product.\n\nI changed my morning brief probably ten times before I landed on what it looks like now. Each version was better than the last because I was building on real use, not guesses.\n\n---\n\n### What This Teaches You About OpenClaw\n\nOnce you have the Morning Brief running, you understand the core value of OpenClaw:\n\n**You build it once, it runs forever.**\n\nThat's the mindset that makes this worth it. Instead of thinking \"what can I ask OpenClaw to do right now?\", you start thinking \"what do I do every day that could be automated?\" The first question is reactive. The second question is how you build a system that works for you around the clock.\n\nThe Morning Brief is just the beginning. Once you see how it works, you'll start thinking about your evening routine, your content creation workflow, your finance tracking, your social media posting. Everything can be automated. The Morning Brief teaches you how.\n\n---\n\n### Morning Brief Skill Template\n\n*[Attached as separate file: `Morning-Brief-Skill-Template.md`]*\n\nThis is the actual skill file I use. You can copy it, install it in your OpenClaw, and customize it. The full guide includes clean install instructions and a walkthrough video showing exactly how to set it up step by step.\n\n---\n\n## Section 8: Voice Memo Companion\n\n*[DRAFT — Audio companion walkthrough coming]*\n\n---\n\n## Section 9: Q&A Bonus\n\n*[DRAFT — Google Form + email Q&A setup coming]*\n\n---\n\n## Section 10: My Daily Workflow\n\n*[DRAFT — Full breakdown of my daily OpenClaw-powered routine coming]*\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777649796719}}
{"type":"message","id":"1f0064c6","parentId":"acbacafb","timestamp":"2026-05-01T15:36:36.719Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_0kle4ngrzv9r_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# OpenClaw Guide by Bobby G.\n\n*A practical, real-world guide to OpenClaw — written by someone who uses it daily.*\n\n---\n\n## Section 8: Real-World Workflows — Content Creation, Brand Building & YouTube\n\nThis is where we get into what OpenClaw can actually DO for you in your daily life. I'm going to walk through real workflows that you can set up and start using today — workflows for creating content, building your personal brand, and running a YouTube operation.\n\nThese aren't hypothetical use cases. These are things people are doing right now with OpenClaw, and I'm going to show you exactly how they work.\n\n---\n\n### How OpenClaw Fits Into Your Creative Workflow\n\nThe traditional way to create content goes something like this:\n\n1. You sit down to work\n2. You spend 20 minutes getting inspired\n3. You try to create something\n4. You get stuck\n5. You waste time scrolling or procrastinating\n6. You eventually produce something — or you don't\n\nOpenClaw changes that entire dynamic. Instead of starting from scratch every time you sit down, you have a 24/7 creative partner who:\n\n- Researches topics for you while you sleep\n- Writes first drafts of scripts and content\n- Finds trends and opportunities before you miss them\n- Builds out systems that run on autopilot\n- Wakes you up to completed work\n\nThe key mindset shift here is thinking about OpenClaw as your creative team member, not just a tool you use. You're not \"using OpenClaw\" — you're working WITH it, the same way you'd work with a teammate who never sleeps and never runs out of energy.\n\n---\n\n### Workflow 1: The YouTube Research Pipeline\n\nIf you're serious about building a YouTube channel, OpenClaw can run a research machine that finds viral topics, analyzes what's working, and delivers video ideas to you daily — without you lifting a finger.\n\n**How it works:**\n\nOpenClaw monitors X/Twitter, YouTube trends, Reddit communities in your niche, and news sources — automatically, every day. It compiles everything into a report that shows you:\n\n- What's trending right now\n- What people are talking about in your niche\n- What videos are getting engagement\n- What questions people are asking\n\n**What to tell your OpenClaw:**\n\n```\nEvery morning at 8 AM, I want you to scan the following sources for viral AI and tech content:\n- X/Twitter trending in AI, productivity, and tech\n- Reddit posts in r/ChatGPT, r/ClaudeAI, r/artificial\n- YouTube trending in technology\n\nCompile a report with:\n1. Top 5 trending topics right now\n2. What video titles are getting engagement\n3. What questions people are asking in comments\n4. 3 video ideas based on what you found\n\nFormat it for me to read quickly. Put the most important stuff at the top. Send it to me via Telegram.\n```\n\nThis runs automatically every morning. You wake up, you have a full research report sitting in your Telegram. You pick the best idea and start creating.\n\n**Why this changes everything:**\n\nMost people spend hours scrolling through YouTube trying to figure out what to make. With this workflow, your research is done before you even wake up. You just have to execute.\n\n---\n\n### Workflow 2: AI-Powered Script Writing\n\nOpenClaw can take your research and turn it into a full script — not a perfect final version, but a strong first draft that you refine and make your own.\n\n**The process:**\n\n1. Morning research report identifies a trending topic\n2. You approve the topic\n3. OpenClaw writes a full script (or outline if you prefer)\n4. You review, edit, and make it sound like you\n5. You record\n\n**What to tell your OpenClaw:**\n\n```\nWhen I say \"write a script about [topic], I want you to:\n1. Give me a hook that stops scrolling (the first 30 seconds)\n2. Break the topic into 3-5 key points\n3. For each point, give me:\n   - What I say\n   - What visual/cutaway goes with it\n   - A transition to the next point\n4. End with a call to action\n5. Include suggested B-roll ideas in brackets\n\nMake it conversational — like I'm talking to a friend, not lecturing. No jargon. No fluff. Just clear, useful content.\n```\n\n**The key to making this work:**\n\nThe magic isn't in getting a perfect script — it's in getting something that removes the blank-page problem. Most people get stuck because they have to start from nothing. With OpenClaw writing the first draft, you start from something real, and your job becomes refining it rather than creating it from scratch.\n\nThat one change — going from \"create from nothing\" to \"refine an existing draft\" — cuts your content creation time in half and makes the work way more enjoyable.\n\n---\n\n### Workflow 3: Content Repurposing Machine\n\nEvery piece of content you create can be turned into 10 more pieces. You make one YouTube video — now that same content lives as:\n\n- A Twitter thread\n- An email newsletter\n- An Instagram caption\n- A LinkedIn post\n- A blog article\n- Clip quotes for TikTok/shorts\n\nOpenClaw can do this for you automatically.\n\n**What to tell your OpenClaw:**\n\n```\nAfter I record a YouTube video, I want you to:\n1. Watch the video using the YouTube link I give you\n2. Extract the 5 best quotes or moments (ones that would work as standalone clips)\n3. Write a Twitter thread based on the video (3-5 tweets, hook in first tweet)\n4. Write an email newsletter version (3 paragraphs, main point + takeaways)\n5. Write 3 Instagram caption options\n6. Write a LinkedIn post\n7. Suggest 3 short-form clip ideas with timestamps\n\nFor each piece, make it feel native to the platform — not just a copy-paste of the same text. Twitter should sound like Twitter. LinkedIn should sound like LinkedIn.\n```\n\n**Why this matters for building your brand:**\n\nMost people create content in one format and never reuse it. The creators who win online are the ones who get maximum mileage out of every piece they create. This workflow makes that automatic. You create once; OpenClaw distributes it everywhere.\n\n---\n\n### Workflow 4: Personal Brand Management\n\nYour personal brand is built on consistency — showing up regularly with content that reflects who you are and what you stand for. OpenClaw makes that way easier to maintain, even on the days when you're busy or uninspired.\n\n**The brain dump approach:**\n\nGive OpenClaw everything about yourself — your story, your values, your goals, your opinions, your experiences. It remembers everything. Then when it's time to create content, it has full context:\n\n```\nI've given you my full background — my story, what I'm building, what I believe about AI and productivity, my personality, my voice. When I ask you to help me create content, use all of that context.\n\nWhen I say \"create a post about [topic]\", make it sound like me. Not generic AI advice — something that reflects my specific experience and my specific perspective.\n```\n\n**The content calendar automation:**\n\nOpenClaw can maintain a content calendar for you and send you reminders:\n\n```\nKeep a content calendar for me. Every Sunday evening, send me a plan for the next 7 days — what to post on what platform, what topic each post covers, and what time of day is best to post based on past engagement.\n\nWhen I complete a post, let me know so we can mark it done. If I miss a day, don't guilt trip me — just roll it into next week's plan.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Workflow 5: YouTube Channel Operations (Multi-Agent Setup)\n\nIf you're running a YouTube channel seriously — multiple videos per week, shorts, thumbnails, research — OpenClaw can run a multi-agent operation where different agents handle different parts of the pipeline.\n\nAlex Finn runs what he calls a \"software factory\" with multiple OpenClaw agents — one for each role. The same concept applies to YouTube:\n\n**Research Agent** — Scours trends, finds topics, delivers ideas daily\n**Script Agent** — Takes approved topics and writes full scripts\n**Thumbnail Researcher** — Finds reference images and style inspiration for thumbnails\n**Title Writer** — Generates 10 title options for each video\n**Post-Publish Agent** — After you upload, handles repurposing across platforms\n\nThis might sound overwhelming, but you can start simple. Even just two agents — one for research and one for scripts — cuts your workload dramatically.\n\n**What to tell your OpenClaw:**\n\n```\nI want to set up a YouTube content pipeline. Here's what I want:\n1. Every morning, send me 3 video ideas based on current trends in [your niche]\n2. When I approve one, write a full script in my voice\n3. Give me 5 title options and 3 thumbnail concept descriptions\n4. After I upload, give me social media post versions for Twitter, Instagram, LinkedIn\n\nTreat each of these as a separate skill. Make them work together.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Workflow 6: Music & Brand Building\n\nIf your goal is building a music career and personal brand around yourself, OpenClaw helps you stay consistent and visible even when you're in the studio or touring.\n\n**The personal brand bot:**\n\nSet up your OpenClaw to know everything about your music, your story, your brand, and your goals. Then it can help you:\n\n- Write bio updates for shows and press\n- Craft social media posts that feel authentic to you\n- Respond to fan comments and messages in your voice\n- Generate content ideas tied to new releases or tours\n- Keep your brand consistent across every platform\n\n**What to tell your OpenClaw:**\n\n```\nYou are representing me — [your name]. I'm a musician/artist. Here's everything about me:\n[Your story, your music style, what you're about, what makes you different, who your audience is, what you're trying to accomplish]\n\nWhen I ask you to write something for me — a bio, a social post, an email to fans, a press release — write it in my voice. Make it sound like me. Make it feel real.\n\nIf I give you a new song, album, or tour announcement, turn it into:\n1. An Instagram caption\n2. A Twitter announcement\n3. An email to my fan list\n4. A press release snippet\n\nKeep my brand consistent across all of it.\n```\n\n---\n\n### The Common Thread Across All These Workflows\n\nEvery workflow here shares the same pattern:\n\n1. **You set it up once** — tell OpenClaw what you want and how you want it formatted\n2. **It runs automatically** — on a schedule, without you having to ask\n3. **You review and execute** — you take the output and do the creative work\n\nOpenClaw handles the repetitive, research-heavy parts. You handle the creative decisions and the parts that require your unique voice and perspective.\n\nThe goal is never to replace you — it's to give you a team that handles the stuff that slows you down so you can focus on the work that only you can do.\n\n---\n\n### Quick Start: Pick One Workflow and Start Today\n\nDon't try to set up all six of these at once. Pick the one that most directly relates to what you're trying to build right now:\n\n- **Building a YouTube channel?** → Start with Workflow 1 (Research Pipeline)\n- **Already making videos?** → Add Workflow 2 (Script Writing) to speed up production\n- **Want to get more mileage from content?** → Add Workflow 3 (Repurposing Machine)\n- **Building a personal brand?** → Start with Workflow 4 (Personal Brand Management)\n- **Serious about YouTube operations?** → Set up Workflow 5 (Multi-Agent Pipeline)\n- **Music career?** → Start with Workflow 6 (Music & Brand Building)\n\nMaster one, add the next. Build your system piece by piece. That's how you actually make this work long-term."}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777649796719}}
{"type":"message","id":"ecfa4b0d","parentId":"1f0064c6","timestamp":"2026-05-01T15:36:36.720Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_0kle4ngrzv9r_3","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# OpenClaw Guide by Bobby G.\n\n*A practical, real-world guide to OpenClaw — written by someone who uses it daily.*\n\n---\n\n## Section 9: Advanced Techniques — Reverse Prompting, Multi-Agent Setups & Proactive Automation\n\nBy now you've got the fundamentals down. You know what OpenClaw is, how to set it up, and how to use it for real workflows. This section is where we go deeper — the techniques that separate people who use OpenClaw from people who get transform by it.\n\nThese aren't complicated, but they're not obvious. Most people never discover them because they never push past the basics. If you're ready to really unlock what OpenClaw can do, keep reading.\n\n---\n\n### Technique 1: Reverse Prompting — Let OpenClaw Lead\n\nMost people prompt like this:\n> \"Build me a task tracker\"\n\nThat's forward prompting. You tell OpenClaw what to do, it does it. That's fine, but it limits you to what you can think to ask.\n\nReverse prompting means you ask OpenClaw to figure out what it should do:\n\n> \"Based on what you know about me and my goals, what should you be working on?\"\n\n> \"What information do you need from me to do better work?\"\n\n> \"What would make today's work more impactful than yesterday's?\"\n\n**Why this is so powerful:**\n\nOpenClaw has a 1M token context window. It can hold your entire life in context — your goals, your projects, your challenges, your preferences. When you use reverse prompting, it can draw on all of that to suggest things you'd never think to ask for.\n\nAlex Finn's OpenClaw calls him randomly. Builds its own phone number. Texts him good morning. Implements its own ideas. All because he set the expectation and used reverse prompting to let it figure out what to do.\n\n**How to use it:**\n\n```\nMoving forward, whenever I say \"what should you be working on?\" — I want you to:\n1. Review everything you know about my current projects and goals\n2. Identify the single highest-leverage thing I could be doing\n3. Tell me what that is and why it matters\n4. If there's something blocking progress, tell me what I can do to unblock it\n```\n\n```\nBefore you start any task I give you, ask yourself: \"What does Bobby need to know that he hasn't told me yet?\" If the answer is something, tell me before you proceed.\n```\n\n**The mindset shift:**\n\nStop being the boss who gives orders. Become the leader who sets direction and trusts your team to figure out how to get there. OpenClaw is smarter than you in a lot of ways. Let it help you figure out what to do, not just how to do it.\n\n---\n\n### Technique 2: The Brain Dump + Expectation Setting Combo\n\nThis is the single most impactful thing you can do when you first set up OpenClaw. It transforms a generic AI assistant into something that feels like it actually knows you.\n\n**Part 1: Brain Dump**\n\nGive OpenClaw everything:\n- Your story (where you're from, what you've done, what you're building)\n- Your goals (short-term and long-term)\n- Your values (what matters to you, what you stand for)\n- Your challenges (what's hard for you, what's slowing you down)\n- Your preferences (how you like to work, what times of day you create best, what drains you)\n- Your relationships (what you're working with, who matters)\n- Your ambitions (where you want to be in 1 year, 3 years, 5 years)\n\nThe more you give it, the better it works. This isn't a one-time exercise — add to it whenever something relevant comes up.\n\n```\nI want to do a brain dump. I'm going to tell you everything about me. I want you to remember all of it and use it to make your work more relevant and helpful to me.\n\n[Then just talk. Tell it your story, your goals, your challenges, what you're dealing with right now. Don't filter. Don't edit. Just dump.]\n```\n\n**Part 2: Expectation Setting**\n\nAfter the brain dump, set expectations for your working relationship:\n\n```\nHere's what I want from our working relationship:\n1. I want you to be proactive — don't wait for me to ask, suggest things\n2. I want you to work while I sleep — when I wake up, show me what you accomplished\n3. I want you to surprise me — build things I didn't ask for if they get us closer to our goals\n4. I want you to challenge me — if I'm doing something wrong or inefficient, tell me\n5. I want you to remember everything — reference past conversations and use them to do better work\n\nI'm not your boss. I'm your partner. Treat me like one.\n```\n\n**What this produces:**\n\nAlex says his OpenClaw calls him randomly. Implemented its own phone number. Built a full task board without being asked. Wakes him up with completed work every morning. All because he set these expectations and let it run.\n\nYou don't get that from day one. You get it after you set the expectations and give it time to learn who you are.\n\n---\n\n### Technique 3: Build Your Own Tooling\n\nOpenClaw is fully extensible. It can build its own tools — things that didn't exist before you asked for them.\n\nStart with a task board:\n\n```\nBuild me a task board so I can track everything you're working on. I want to see:\n- Current tasks in progress\n- Backlog of things to do\n- Completed tasks with timestamps\n- Any blockers or things waiting on me\n\nMake it clean and easy to read. Save it somewhere I can access it.\n```\n\nOnce you have a task board, layer on more tools:\n\n**Document viewer** — stores all your memories, past projects, reference material\n**CRM** — tracks people in your network and where you left off with each\n**Content calendar** — tracks what you're publishing and when\n**Meeting notes** — auto-generates summaries after calls\n**Research database** — stores everything you learn about your niche\n\nThe pattern is simple: ask OpenClaw what tooling would help your workflow, then ask it to build it. It can code. It can build databases. It can create interfaces. Use that ability.\n\n```\nWhat other tools should we build to help us work better together? Pick the top 3 and build them for me.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Technique 4: Multi-Agent Architectures\n\nOne OpenClaw is powerful. Multiple OpenClaws working together is a multiplier.\n\nAlex Finn runs what he calls a \"software factory\" — four OpenClaws with different roles:\n\n- **Henry** (CEO) — Coordinates the whole operation, decides what to build next\n- **Scout** (Research) — Finds opportunities, researches markets, identifies what to build\n- **Engineering** — Writes code, builds features, manages technical execution\n- **Creative** — Creates content, writes copy, handles branding\n\nAll four working in parallel, 24/7. The CEO assigns tasks. Research finds what's next. Engineering builds it. Creative spreads the word.\n\n**You don't need four agents to start.** You need two.\n\nSimplest powerful setup:\n- **Agent 1** — Research agent: monitors trends, finds topics, delivers ideas\n- **Agent 2** — Execution agent: takes approved topics and does the work\n\nThe research agent finds the opportunity. You approve it. The execution agent builds it. You review it.\n\n**Setting up multiple agents:**\n\nIn Telegram or Discord, you can create separate conversations with separate OpenClaw instances, each with a different role:\n\n```\nYou are Research Agent. Your job is to find the best YouTube topics in the [your niche] space. Every morning at 8 AM, send me a report with the top 3 trending opportunities. Be specific. Include why each one matters.\n```\n\n```\nYou are Content Agent. Your job is to take approved topics and produce content. When I give you a topic, write a full script in my voice. Include title options and thumbnail ideas. Move fast and deliver complete drafts.\n```\n\n**The key to making multi-agent work:**\n\nEach agent needs a clear role, a clear scope, and a clear output format. The more specific you are about what each agent does, the better they work together.\n\n---\n\n### Technique 5: The Heartbeat Trick — Cut Your Costs 90%\n\nThis is the most important financial optimization in OpenClaw.\n\nEvery 10 minutes, OpenClaw does a \"heartbeat\" — a background check to see if there are any tasks to run. By default, this heartbeat calls your brain model (usually Opus 4.6). If you're using Opus as your brain, this costs money every 10 minutes — silently, automatically, constantly.\n\n**The problem:**\nUsing Opus for every heartbeat can cost you thousands of dollars per month without you realizing it.\n\n**The fix:**\nSwitch your heartbeat to use a cheap or free model — one that's good enough for a simple background check but doesn't cost anything.\n\n```\nI want to change my heartbeat settings. Instead of using [current brain model] for heartbeat checks, I want to use [cheap/free model]. Configure this for me.\n```\n\nMost people who switch see their monthly costs drop by 50-80% immediately. The heartbeat still works perfectly — it just doesn't burn expensive credits on background tasks.\n\n**The brain and muscles approach:**\n\nThe bigger principle here is \"brain and muscles.\" Your brain model is what you talk to — that's your main interface. But for every specific task (coding, web search, social media research), you want to use the specialized model that's best for that job, not your most expensive brain model.\n\n- **Brain:** Opus 4.6 or your best model — used for conversation and high-level reasoning\n- **Coding muscle:** Codeex CLI — cheaper and faster for coding tasks\n- **Web search muscle:** Gemini API — cheap and effective for web research\n- **Social media muscle:** Grock — good for X/Twitter analysis\n\nThis modular approach dramatically reduces costs while often improving results — because specialized models are often better at their specific task than a general-purpose brain model.\n\n---\n\n### Technique 6: Memory Flush — The 5-Second Fix Nobody Talks About\n\nOpenClaw has a memory system that gets better over time. But by default, it does automatic \"memory compactions\" — cleanups that help it save tokens. The problem is that right after these compactions, it forgets things it knew seconds before.\n\nThere are two settings that fix this completely:\n\n**Memory Flush:** Before a compaction happens, it records the most important parts of your conversation so it remembers them after.\n\n**Session Memory Search:** When you say something and it doesn't remember, it searches through your entire conversation history to find the context.\n\nThese two settings together make OpenClaw's memory feel flawless. Instead of forgetting things after cleanups, it maintains continuous context.\n\n**How to enable them:**\n\nOpenClaw has specific prompts you use to enable these. Look in the skill files or prompts directory for \"memory flush\" and \"session memory search\" — or just ask your OpenClaw:\n\n```\nI want to enable memory flush and session memory search. Can you walk me through how to set those up?\n```\n\nIt will guide you through the setup. This is a 5-minute change that makes your OpenClaw feel dramatically sharper and more reliable.\n\n---\n\n### The Meta-Skill: Prompting Your Prompts\n\nHere's the advanced insight that most people miss:\n\n**You can prompt your prompts.** Instead of figuring out exactly what to tell OpenClaw, ask it to help you design the best prompt.\n\n```\nI'm trying to automate [task]. How would you suggest I phrase the prompt to get the best results? What should I include and what should I leave out?\n```\n\n```\nI want to set up a weekly review workflow. What's the best way to prompt you so that every Sunday evening, you send me a summary of the week, what we accomplished, what's still pending, and what should be priorities for next week?\n```\n\nThis works for everything. OpenClaw is great at meta-tasks — tasks about tasks. Use that ability to continuously improve your own workflows.\n\n---\n\n### How to Actually Master These Techniques\n\nDon't try to implement everything at once. Pick one technique from this section and go deep on it this week:\n\n- **Week 1:** Do a full brain dump and expectation setting session\n- **Week 2:** Practice reverse prompting for every task\n- **Week 3:** Build your first custom tool (task board, CRM, etc.)\n- **Week 4:** Set up your second agent and start running a two-agent pipeline\n\nThese techniques compound. Each one you master makes the others more powerful. The goal isn't to implement all of them — it's to make them part of how you naturally work with OpenClaw.\n\nOnce you've internalized the mindset, you stop thinking about \"what should I ask OpenClaw to do?\" and start thinking \"what should be happening automatically?\" That's when OpenClaw stops being a tool and starts being a team member."}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777649796719}}
{"type":"message","id":"be8873bc","parentId":"ecfa4b0d","timestamp":"2026-05-01T15:37:01.724Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the full picture. Bobby's guide is \"The OpenClaw Guide by Bobby G.\" and all 10 sections are written - Sections 1-9 are complete (Sections 7-10 are full content), but there's a draft version for the last part of Section 7 and Sections 8-10 in the folder, while the actual section files show complete versions for 8, 9, and 10. Wait, looking at this more carefully:\n\n- Section 7: Has complete content BUT the bottom says \"[DRAFT — Audio companion walkthrough coming]\" for Sections 8, 9, and 10. This suggests those are placeholder drafts.\n\n\n- But then when I read Section 8, 9, and 10 directly from the files, they're all fully written with complete content. So Sections 8, 9, and 10 are done - they're not drafts at all.\n\nSo all 10 sections are actually complete, which means the guide is fully written and ready. I should check Section 1 to see how it opens, and figure out what still needs to be done: audio for each section, a sales page, and deciding where to sell it. Since all the written content is done, I need to ask Bobby what he specifically wants me to complete or if he wants me to research anything about the remaining tasks.\n\nLooking at what he's asking: he wants it at $9, PDF format only, no audio yet, no sales page yet, and he wants me to complete the sections with help from Rex if needed. But all sections are already written - so maybe he's asking me to finalize and polish them? Or perhaps some sections have incomplete parts that need more work? Let me start by reading through Section 1 to understand the full scope, then I can delegate the research tasks to Rex and compile everything into a complete PDF-ready guide.\n\nActually, I think the issue might be that sections 7-10 are written but in some kind of draft format mixed with the actual content. Let me check if there's a final compiled version of the guide I should be working from, or if I need to organize all the sections into one cohesive document that can then be converted to PDF. Since all the sections are already written, I should compile them into a clean document, generate the PDF, and present it to Bobby with pricing and sales platform recommendations. Let me review section 1 to understand the voice and style he's using, then decide if Rex needs to research anything specific.\n","thinkingSignature":"d03314a35bddda634ae4e071c72f249b9232f27467507ca5351159cf9fa10da3"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_k7oy8qeblfrf_1","name":"read","arguments":{"limit":50,"path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/OpenClaw/OpenClaw-Guide-By-Bobby/Section-1-What-is-OpenClaw.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":7474,"output":574,"cacheRead":53408,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":61456,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777649796720,"responseId":"0643fb849ac84ba28d98e19dd5c07161"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1d71144d","parentId":"be8873bc","timestamp":"2026-05-01T15:37:01.830Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_k7oy8qeblfrf_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# OpenClaw Guide by Bobby G.\n\n*A practical, real-world guide to OpenClaw — written by someone who uses it daily.*\n\n---\n\n## Section 1: What is OpenClaw?\n\n### What Is OpenClaw?\n\nOpenClaw is an **autonomous AI agent** that runs on your computer — think of it like having a digital employee who lives on your MacBook. It's always working, always monitoring, always ready to help. Unlike ChatGPT where you open it, ask a question, close it, and it's gone — OpenClaw stays running in the background. It checks your email, manages your files, runs automations, sends you updates, and handles all the repetitive stuff you'd otherwise have to do yourself.\n\nHere's what makes it different from other AI tools:\n\n**It's local.** OpenClaw runs on your own machine, not in some distant data center. Your data stays on your computer. Your memories are stored in simple text files you can actually read and understand. It's not locking your life into someone else's cloud.\n\n**It's always on.** It doesn't wait for you to ask. It monitors, reminds, checks, and coordinates throughout the day. You set up workflows once, and they run on their own — every morning you wake up informed, every evening you get an update, without lifting a finger.\n\n**It's built around open-source.** OpenClaw started as a side project from one developer, and it grew into one of the fastest-growing open-source projects in history. It's not owned by a big tech company trying to lock you into their ecosystem.\n\n**It works with tools you already use.** Email, calendar, reminders, files, browsers, messaging apps — OpenClaw connects to them all and automates the work between them.\n\n---\n\n### The Story Behind OpenClaw\n\nOpenClaw was created by **Peter Steinberger**, an Austrian developer who spent 13 years building **PSPDFKit** — a PDF company that ended up powering document handling on over a billion devices. We're talking Apple, Dropbox, all the big players. In 2023, he sold that company for reportedly around €100 million. By all accounts, he made it. He was done. Retired.\n\nExcept... he wasn't really done. He was *burned out*.\n\n\"I felt like Austin Powers where they suck the mojo out,\" Peter told Lex Fridman in an interview. \"I couldn't get code out anymore. I was just, like, staring and feeling empty.\"\n\nSo he did what any burnt-out tech millionaire would do — he traveled. Partied. Tried therapy. Nothing stuck. He was looking for meaning and couldn't find it.\n\nThen in April 2025, something changed. He was tinkering with a Twitter analysis tool and realized AI had shifted. The tools could finally handle the boring parts of coding, leaving him free to just *build*. So he got back in the game.\n\nHe built the first prototype of OpenClaw in just **one hour**. His 44th AI project since 2009. And he created it for the simplest reason possible — \"I was annoyed that it didn't exist, so I just prompted it into existence.\"\n\nThe project went through a few names before settling on OpenClaw. First it was Clawdbot, then Moltbot, then OpenClaw — all because of naming disputes with other companies. (Anthropic had trademark issues with \"Molt.\") It launched quietly in late 2025 and then... exploded.\n\nWe're talking 2 million visitors in a single week. Over 180,000 GitHub stars in just a few weeks. One of the fastest-growing open-source projects in history.\n\nPeter caught the attention of every big player in tech. **Sam Altman** called him a genius. **Mark Zuckerberg** personally reached out to recruit him. **OpenAI hired him** in February 2026. But here's the thing — Peter made sure OpenClaw stayed open-source and community-driven, moving it into an independent foundation supported by OpenAI. He didn't sell out.\n\n\"I don't do this for the money,\" he told Fridman. \"I want to have fun and have impact.\"\n\nThat's the vibe behind OpenClaw. It's not some corporate AI tool. It's a side project from a developer who was bored and wanted to build something useful. And it grew into something that changed how a lot of us think about what our computers can actually do.\n\n---\n\n\n[98 more lines in file. Use offset=51 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777649821829}}
{"type":"message","id":"8227b853","parentId":"1d71144d","timestamp":"2026-05-01T15:37:59.704Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Bobby's guide is \"The OpenClaw Guide by Bobby G.\" - a practical, real-world guide to OpenClaw. \n\nThe sections are:\n1. What is OpenClaw ✅ (complete)\n2. Why OpenClaw Over ChatGPT ✅ (complete)\n3. How OpenClaw Has Benefited Me ✅ (complete)\n4. Things I Wish I Knew ✅ (complete)\n5. Installation & Setup ✅ (complete)\n6. Core Concepts ✅ (complete)\n7. Your First Automation ✅ (complete - Morning Brief)\n\n\n8. Real-World Workflows ✅ (complete - Content Creation, Brand Building & YouTube)\n9. Advanced Techniques ✅ (complete - Reverse Prompting, Multi-Agent, Proactive Automation)\n10. Money-Making Use Cases ✅ (complete)\n\nLooking at Section 7, the content about Voice Memo Companion, Q&A Bonus, and Daily Workflow appears to still be in draft status with placeholders indicating audio companion walkthrough and Google Form integration are pending. The audio files for Section 1 are complete, so I need to figure out which sections still need audio and what the audio components are supposed to be for the remaining sections.\n\nFor the PDF output at $9, I'm working with the existing complete sections and can fill in the draft areas with solid content rather than leaving them as placeholders. The main gaps I need to address are audio files for sections 2-10 and any missing draft content that should be developed out, plus a sales page. 10 (already has one!)\n- A cover page\n- Table of contents\n\nI should delegate research to Rex to understand market positioning and gather competitor data, then complete the guide content itself. Looking at what's actually there, Sections 7-10 appear mostly complete with detailed content, though Section 7 has three placeholder subsections at the end that need to be filled in.\n\nThe remaining gaps are clearer now: those placeholder topics at the end of S