{"type":"message","id":"aa890a92","parentId":"ad350225","timestamp":"2026-05-01T16:57:50.344Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait - Bobby said \"there is nothing to listen to here\" - meaning the audio file I sent earlier (the first voice memo) was not working for him. And he said to use the system voice with no specific voice flag. Let me re-read what I did - I used `say -v 'Voice 1'` which explicitly specified a voice. He wants me to use just the system default voice.\n\nActually looking at his message again - he said \"there is nothing to listen to here. you should be using the system voice ( no specific voice specified)\" - this is about the audio that was in the inbound message. The inbound media was a voice memo FROM Bobby (or possibly a failed/empty file). But he says \"there is nothing to listen to here\" - which might mean the audio was empty or unplayable.\n \nHmm, but the media path points to an inbound file from B G, so that was Bobby's voice memo to me - and he says there's nothing to listen to there. So either the file didn't come through properly or it got lost in transmission. I think what he's actually saying is the audio I sent him earlier wasn't working on his end, so he wants me to use just `say` with no voice flags to get the system default. The \"there is nothing to listen to here\" could mean my voice memo didn't play, or the voice file itself might have issues, or possibly something else happened when he was trying to hear my message.\n\nLet me just move forward with the plan to send the link and use the default voice.\n","thinkingSignature":"5d50455538064077e2887a2a859bb057aed869b67a2539725f31debb3ab1519a"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n[[reply_to_current]] That was me using Voice 1 explicitly — won't do that again. From now on it's just `say` with the system default, no flags.\n\nThe questionnaire is still waiting for you here — tap it whenever you're ready:\n[http://192.168.1.162:8790/questionnaire.ht