{"type":"message","id":"a030aef6","parentId":"8f143e74","timestamp":"2026-05-01T19:34:10.332Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Bobby is saying the microphone isn't working at all - because the yellow recording dot that usually appears in the menu bar when an app is using the microphone isn't showing up. This means the page isn't actually accessing the microphone.\n\nThe issue is likely that Safari's Web Speech API doesn't work well in a local file or localhost context for speech recognition. The Web Speech API's speech recognition (`SpeechRecognition`) is different from just using `getUserMedia` for audio recording.\n\nThe `getUserMedia` approach I have should work for audio recording - but the issue might be that the MediaRecorder approach requires microphone permission to be granted first, and that's a browser permission that has to be explicitly given.\n\nLet me check if the microphone permission is actually being requested. When you call `navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({ audio: true })`, the browser should prompt for permission. If it doesn't show up, it might be because:\n\n1. The browser has already blocked microphone access for localhost\n\n\n2. Safari needs explicit permission\n3. The getUserMedia call itself might be failing silently\n\nI think the simplest approach here is to rebuild this using native macOS speech recognition through a Python script that runs on the server side and handles the audio transcription, rather than relying on the browser's Web Speech API. This would bypass all the permission issues entirely.\n","thinkingSignature":"81ec58c8632489ad58c73228edc27863b26b9411f13fa1a23dbc310ca7f5c5ac"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\nGot it — the mic isn't even being asked. Safari's Web Speech API doesn't work well from local pages. Let me rebuild with a different approach.\n\nInstead of relying on Safari's speech recognition, I'll have the server handle transcription using your Mac's native speech tools. You