{"type":"message","id":"9aa0bb1b","parentId":"58748fe4","timestamp":"2026-05-01T19:37:50.463Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`rev` doesn't have transcription functionality. Let me think of a better approach.\n\nSince Safari Web Speech API doesn't work from local pages, I should:\n1. Use `npx whisper` for transcription instead\n2. OR use the `say` command to speak and then use a speech-to-text tool\n\nActually, let me think about what Bobby wants:\n- He presses a mic button in Safari\n- He talks\n- Audio gets recorded\n- It gets transcribed (on the server)\n- Dean responds with voice\n\nFor the transcription, I could use:\n1. `whisper` CLI - but it's not installed at ~/Downloads/... it's available via some path\n\n\n2. OpenAI's Whisper API would work but I'd need an API key\n3. I could leverage macOS built-ins like `say` for text-to-speech and `asr` for speech recognition, though `asr` is designed for file transcription rather than live audio\n4. Browser-based solutions might work better—I'm thinking a fallback approach where I try Web Speech API first, then use a native macOS binary or Chrome extension as alternatives\n\nLooking at what's actually available on the system, `whisper` is accessible at `/opt/homebrew/bin/whisper` according to TOOLS.md, and I could leverage that with a proper fallback chain. The simplest path forward is probably just building the system around using `whisper` directly since it's already installed, rather than trying to make browser APIs work for something they weren't designed for.\n","thinkingSignature":"584c932269a16acc6bd9aa439a14d423815190e9ea96886305db61f1effe5734"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_gszd8ix6aa5r_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"which whisper 2>/dev/null; pip3 show openai-whisper 2>/dev/null | head -3; python3 -c \"import whisper; print('whisper ok')\" 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":8