{"type":"message","id":"861d410c","parentId":"ea87a2c5","timestamp":"2026-05-01T19:49:39.156Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so using HTML parse_mode with `<a href=\"...\">text</a>` works and creates a clickable link. Let me update TOOLS.md with the correct method and make sure all my future link messages use this format.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully - the issue is that when I use the message tool with plain text, Telegram renders it as plain text even if it's a URL. But when I use the HTML `<a href>` tag, it works.\n\nThe message tool doesn't seem to support HTML parse_mode directly. Let me check if I can pass it through the message tool somehow.\n\nBut for now, let me note in TOOLS.md that for clickable links, I need to use HTML anchor tag format via the message tool, and also note that inline button approach I tried earlier also worked. \n\n\nLooking back at what actually worked, the inline button with a url field and the HTML `<a href>` tag both created clickable links, but the plain URL I sent earlier just appeared as plain text with no link preview or tappable link. So the message tool's buttons parameter with a url field is the most reliable approach for creating clickable links.\n\nI should update my documentation and remember these two working patterns: using inline buttons with the url field for tappable links, or using HTML parse mode to wrap the URL in an anchor tag.\n","thinkingSignature":"9e073f04f7abfce35d8f8d48bf49fcacce606c59ef2291836c77d1feb8cd15ca"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nFound it. The inline button approach was the right fix — it shows as a tappable button in Telegram. Let me send it again so you can click:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9tlh7jec9n2u_1","name":"message","arguments":{"action":"send","channel":"telegram","presentation":{"blocks":[{"buttons":[{"label":"Open Telephone","style":"primary","url":"https://bobbys-macbook-air-1.tail358b13.ts.net/telephone.html"}],"