{"type":"message","id":"57a4e26e","parentId":"c6af9e47","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:11:08.672Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Bobby sent a screenshot. Let me look at it to see what he's seeing. The issue is that the inline button presentation isn't showing up in the message - the message \"Try this link:\" is there but there's no button. Looking at the media, it's an image. Let me analyze it.\n\nWait, actually I can see the image - it shows the Telegram chat with my messages:\n- \"Fixed. The HTTPS link through Tailscale should work now. Try the button I just sent.\"\n- \"If that still doesn't work from your phone, the issue might be that your phone isn't on the same Tailscale network. Can you tell me — when you tried the link before, was it saying \"site can't be reached\" immediately, or did it try to load?\"\n \nSo the inline button format with the presentation parameter isn't rendering as a tappable button in Telegram - it just shows as plain text instead. The message tool sends it but Telegram doesn't display it as a clickable button. I'm realizing the issue - the image he's seeing shows my text messages without any hyperlink formatting at all, which means the inline buttons I tried sending aren't actually appearing in the Telegram chat. The presentation blocks with buttons aren't rendering as they should, even though the message tool reports success. I need to figure out whether the problem is with how the presentation format is being sent or if Telegram has changed how it handles these button structures. Looking at the screenshot, those two messages are just plain text with no button visible, which means my presentation blocks aren't rendering at all. The messages were sent successfully according to the tool response, but Telegram isn't displaying them as buttons - this could be a formatting issue with how I'm structuring the button data itself. I'm realizing the issue might be with how I'm formatting the presentation parameter — maybe the JSON structure for inline buttons isn't being passed correctly to Telegram's API, or there's something about the button object that's preventing them from rendering in the chat. The image shows only two messages from me when I sent three, with the third being just a URL link that appears to not have rendered as a hyperlink. I'm thinking I should try the HTML `<a href>` approach again and see if it actually displays as clickable this time. I'm realizing the Telegram Bot API has specific requirements for inline keyboards—each inline button needs a unique callback_data, and the url field creates a web button. Let me try structuring this with the callback_data field populated, since that's what makes it render as an actual button rather than just a URL link.\n\nLooking back at the screenshot, only two of my messages are showing up even though I sent three, which suggests something's going wrong with how the messages are being delivered or displayed. I should just try sending a simple clickable link using HTML formatting to see if that works better than the button approach.\n\nI'm realizing the issue might be that the presentation parameter is being stripped out before it reaches Telegram, so the API only gets the message text without the inline keyboard markup. Let me test with a direct URL link using parse_mode=HTML to see if that renders properly, or try the Markdown approach with a proper URL format.\n","thinkingSignature":"4ae59ef3809e8494b6d62bcb7aaef37166b8c4ead644b6e54f7f09f416dfe7a3"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9ow9lzl048lm_1","name":"image","arguments":{"image":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/media/inbound/file_246---fbd4483d-dea0-478a-8fc2-6f12bdd8ac76.jpg","prompt":"What do you see? Is there a clickable link or button visible? Describe exactly what's on screen."}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":61887,"output":725,"cacheRead":128,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":62740