{"type":"message","id":"a0625076","parentId":"9c7234c7","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:12:53.454Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `buildInlineKeyboard` function only supports `callback_data` buttons, not `url` buttons. This means the inline button format in the `presentation` blocks with `url` fields might not be working as expected.\n\nBut wait - the curl API call with `reply_markup` and `inline_keyboard` with `url` worked! The message had a button. So the Telegram API definitely supports URL buttons.\n\nThe issue is that the `presentation` blocks format I'm using might not be creating the buttons correctly, or the button format might need `callback_data` instead of `url`.\n\nLet me try a different approach - use the Telegram API directly via exec instead of the message tool, since the exec method worked.\n\nActually, the issue might be simpler. The `presentation` format I was using might not be correct for URL buttons. Let me check the OpenClaw docs for how to send URL buttons.\n\nActually wait - looking at the buildInlineKeyboard code, it only maps `text` and `callback_data`. There's no `url` field being mapped. So the URL buttons aren't being created properly by OpenClaw's presentation system.\n\nFor now, let me just use exec to call the Telegram API directly for links. This is the most reliable approach.\n","thinkingSignature":"985a2e6075c135b42299df745381bb3e2ee1def72c7219bf51c59f86cfb93d53"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_u97fg41eoqxn_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"url\" /opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/extensions/telegram/inline-keyboard.js 2>/dev/null | head -20 || find /opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/extensions/telegram -name \"*.js\" | xargs grep -l \"url\" 2>/dev/null | head -5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":169,"output":354,"cacheRead":65024,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":65547,"cost":{"input":0,