{"type":"message","id":"ba2c7c4c","parentId":"80d497ce","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:13:55.758Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so I'm sending it with `parse_mode=HTML` and a proper `<a href=\"...\">text</a>` tag. The last message was sent via curl directly to the Telegram API. It should show as a hyperlink.\n\nBut Bobby keeps saying the buttons I send aren't showing up. Let me try a completely different approach for the presentation blocks format. Maybe the issue is that when `presentation` has a `blocks` structure, it's not building the inline keyboard correctly.\n\nLet me check what actually happens when I send with the message tool + presentation blocks. The key issue might be that the `url` field for buttons in OpenClaw's presentation format is not being translated correctly into Telegram's `inline_keyboard`.\n\nLooking at the buildInlineKeyboard code: it only looks for `callback_data`, not `url`. So buttons with `url` fields are being filtered out entirely! That's why no buttons appear.\n\nLet me check the Telegram bot API docs - for URL buttons, you need `{\"text\": \"label\", \"url\": \"https://...\"}`. But the buildInlineKeyboard function only processes buttons with `callback_data`. It strips out URL buttons completely!\n\nSo the presentation.blocks format for buttons with URLs doesn't work in OpenClaw's Telegram plugin. That's the bug.\n\nBut I've been sending buttons via the message tool and Bobby says the links are clickable in the last 4 messages. So maybe what I'm actually sending IS getting through as a hyperlink somehow. The issue might be something else entirely.\n\nYou know what, let me stop overthinking this. Bobby said \"the last 4 messages i was able to click the links or the hyperlinks so whatever you did for those works remember how to do that.\" So whatever format I used in those last 4 messages worked. What was different about those? They were sent as raw URLs or HTML text_link entities via the curl command.\n\nLet me just commit to using HTML `<a href=\"...\">` format via curl, since that's what's working. I'll update my notes and stop using the message tool's presentation format.\n","thinkingSignature":"14e27afaa4e777228e598448527b38233943eaa1a5fdbe22a87e18b96b06f5f5"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fl69ji7yw74j_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"newText":"### Message Formatting Rules (Telegram)\n- **ALL links must be clickable hyperlinks**\n  - HTML `<a href=\"url\">label</a>` format with `parse_mode=HTML` — this is the ONLY format that works\n  - Example via curl (raw Telegram API):\n    ```\n    curl -s \"https://api.telegram.org/bot${TOKEN}/sendMessage\" \\\n      -d 'chat_id=8212808444&text=<a href=\"https://link\">Open Page</a>&parse_mode=HTML'\n    ```\n  - NEVER use markdown `[text](url)` — it doesn't render as clickable\n  - NEVER use plain text URLs — they don't render as clickable links in Telegram\n  - NEVER use presentation blocks with `url` fields — the Telegram plugin doesn't support URL buttons (only callback_data buttons)\n  - To send a clickable link: use HTML anchor tag format","oldText":"### Message Formatting Rules (Telegram)\n- **ALL links must be sent as inline buttons** — NOT markdown, NOT plain URLs\n  - Use `presentation: {\"blocks\": [{\"type\": \"buttons\", \"buttons\": [{\"label\": \"text\", \"url\": \"https://...\", \"style\": \"primary\"}]}]}`\n  - Plain URLs or markdown `[text](url)` will NOT render as clickable links\n  - Always include a short message BEFORE the button (e.g. \"Tap the link:\")\n  - Example:\n    ```\n    message: \"Tap to open\"\n    presentation: {\"blocks\": [{\"type\": \"buttons\", \"buttons\": [{\"label\": \"Open Page\", \"url\": \"https://link\", \"style\": \"primary\"}]}]}\n    ```"}],"path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace/TOOLS.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":276,"output":858,"cacheRead":66048,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":67182,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777666420737,"responseId":"06443c744a82d66aeb8cd81ed73bcd8b"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1075c75b","parentId":"ba2c7c4c","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:13:55.799Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_fl69ji7yw74j_1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced 1 block(s) in /Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace/TOOLS.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 147 - Tesseract installed at `/opt/homebrew/bin/tesseract` (v5.5.2)\n 148 - Sharp available at `/tmp/node_modules/sharp`\n 149 \n 150 ### Message Formatting Rules (Telegram)\n-151 - **ALL links must be sent as inline buttons** — NOT markdown, NOT plain URLs\n-152   - Use `presentation: {\"blocks\": [{\"type\": \"buttons\", \"buttons\": [{\"label\": \"text\", \"url\": \"https://...\", \"style\": \"primary\"}]}]}`\n-153   - Plain URLs or markdown `[text](url)` will NOT render as clickable links\n-154   - Always include a short message BEFORE the button (e.g. \"Tap the link:\")\n-155   - Example:\n+151 - **ALL links must be clickable hyperlinks**\n+152   - HTML `<a href=\"url\">label</a>` format with `parse_mode=HTML` — this is the ONLY format that works\n+153   - Example via curl (raw Telegram API):\n 156     ```\n-157     message: \"Tap to open\"\n-158     presentation: {\"blocks\": [{\"type\": \"buttons\", \"buttons\": [{\"label\": \"Open Page\", \"url\": \"https://link\", \"style\": \"primary\"}]}]}\n+155     curl -s \"https://api.telegram.org/bot${TOKEN}/sendMessage\" \\\n+156       -d 'chat_id=8212808444&text=<a href=\"https://link\">Open Page</a>&parse_mode=HTML'\n 159     ```\n+158   - NEVER use markdown `[text](url)` — it doesn't render as clickable\n+159   - NEVER use plain text URLs — they don't render as clickable links in Telegram\n+160   - NEVER use presentation blocks with `url` fields — the Telegram plugin doesn't support URL buttons (only callback_data buttons)\n+161   - To send a clickable link: use HTML anchor tag format\n 160 \n 161 ### Voice Memos (System Voice)\n 162 - **Format:** MP3 — always convert with ffmpeg: `say \"text\" -o /tmp/voice.aiff && ffmpeg -i /tmp/voice.aiff /tmp/voice.mp3 -y`\n 163 - **Voice:** System default — no `-v` flag, no voice specification\n     ...","firstChangedLine":151},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777666435798}}
