{"type":"message","id":"717bcedd","parentId":"fa5ffcf6","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:25:18.599Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The core issue is that Whisper transcription is failing. Bobby speaks but the system keeps getting \"Could not transcribe\" — meaning the audio from the browser isn't being successfully transcribed by Whisper.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Instead of trying to fix the transcription pipeline, let me use a completely different approach. The browser has Web Speech API for speech recognition in Safari. Let me check if that's actually working now.\n\nActually wait — the very first telephone.html I built DID try to use SpeechRecognition (window.SpeechRecognition || window.webkitSpeechRecognition) and Bobby said \"Speech not supported\" or the yellow dot never appeared (meaning Safari didn't ask for mic permission).\n\nLet me try a different approach: use the macOS Speech Recognition framework directly on the server side. \n\nI could leverage the system's built-in speech recognition instead of relying on Safari's implementation. Or I could simplify the whole flow — if Bobby speaks and Safari can capture audio through MediaRecorder, the real problem is that Whisper can't transcribe it. Let me trace through what happens when he holds the mic: the browser captures audio and sends it to the server, but Whisper is failing to convert it to text. I should test the recording pipeline directly to see where it's breaking down, or switch to a more reliable speech-to-text option.\n\nActually, macOS has built-in speech recognition through its Speech Synthesis framework, but I need transcription capabilities. Let me check if there's a native `asr` command-line tool available, or I could fall back to a curl-based approach with an OpenAI-compatible API endpoint.\n\nWait—the real issue is that Whisper isn't even getting the audio files to process. The MediaRecorder is generating chunks but they're not being saved properly to disk before Whisper tries to transcribe them. Let me trace through the multipart parsing logic in server.js more carefully.\n\nLooking at how the audio data is being extracted from the multipart response—I'm splitting on the boundary and then taking everything after the first `\\r\\n\\r\\n`, which should be the binary audio data. But the resulting file size is suspiciously small (around 7KB), which doesn't match what a 10-second recording should produce. I need to verify how MediaRecorder is actually chunking and sending the data through the fetch call. The real issue is probably that whisper is failing to process the audio files, or the browser isn't capturing audio successfully from Safari on iOS. Let me think through what else could be going wrong here.\n\nActually, I should test the whole pipeline in reverse — use `say` to generate audio, convert it, and see if whisper can transcribe it back. That'll tell me if the conversion process itself is working. But first, let me try removing all the special characters from the say command and using a simpler, more portable approach with printf and $'...'` quoting instead.\n\nThe real problem is that Bobby can't click links in Telegram unless they're properly formatted with HTML anchor tags. That's the critical issue I need to fix first before worrying about the audio pipeline.","thinkingSignature":"1bac09a05ce45238ae4e00f73cc56d95fe8537769ecde493f6216805f71d6054"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xrl2arm4i66e_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"tail -20 ~/.openclaw/logs/telephone.log 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":91731,"output":653,"cacheRead":224,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":92608,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777667107378,"responseId":"06443f24d3bff5b44f7f4f74bfb5708b"}}
