{"type":"message","id":"210e2864","parentId":"6eb7aaca","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:28:25.169Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's an `openai-http-api.md` file that probably describes how to call the gateway's OpenAI-compatible API. Let me read that.","thinkingSignature":"2299c0faa179a8cb18436c1b10e43ff2cca7c3d45d344bdf681d1de012b1ee02"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ftxlx6ql1hok_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md | head -80"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":255,"output":75,"cacheRead":106464,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":106794,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777667304088,"responseId":"06443fe884b3597ea8bea08930118f22"}}
{"type":"message","id":"50104b8e","parentId":"210e2864","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:28:25.238Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ftxlx6ql1hok_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nsummary: \"Expose an OpenAI-compatible /v1/chat/completions HTTP endpoint from the Gateway\"\nread_when:\n  - Integrating tools that expect OpenAI Chat Completions\ntitle: \"OpenAI chat completions\"\n---\n\nOpenClaw’s Gateway can serve a small OpenAI-compatible Chat Completions endpoint.\n\nThis endpoint is **disabled by default**. Enable it in config first.\n\n- `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n- Same port as the Gateway (WS + HTTP multiplex): `http://<gateway-host>:<port>/v1/chat/completions`\n\nWhen the Gateway’s OpenAI-compatible HTTP surface is enabled, it also serves:\n\n- `GET /v1/models`\n- `GET /v1/models/{id}`\n- `POST /v1/embeddings`\n- `POST /v1/responses`\n\nUnder the hood, requests are executed as a normal Gateway agent run (same codepath as `openclaw agent`), so routing/permissions/config match your Gateway.\n\n## Authentication\n\nUses the Gateway auth configuration.\n\nCommon HTTP auth paths:\n\n- shared-secret auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"token\"` or `\"password\"`):\n  `Authorization: Bearer <token-or-password>`\n- trusted identity-bearing HTTP auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"trusted-proxy\"`):\n  route through the configured identity-aware proxy and let it inject the\n  required identity headers\n- private-ingress open auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"`):\n  no auth header required\n\nNotes:\n\n- When `gateway.auth.mode=\"token\"`, use `gateway.auth.token` (or `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN`).\n- When `gateway.auth.mode=\"password\"`, use `gateway.auth.password` (or `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_PASSWORD`).\n- When `gateway.auth.mode=\"trusted-proxy\"`, the HTTP request must come from a\n  configured trusted proxy source; same-host loopback proxies require explicit\n  `gateway.auth.trustedProxy.allowLoopback = true`.\n- If `gateway.auth.rateLimit` is configured and too many auth failures occur, the endpoint returns `429` with `Retry-After`.\n\n## Security boundary (important)\n\nTreat this endpoint as a **full operator-access** surface for the gateway instance.\n\n- HTTP bearer auth here is not a narrow per-user scope model.\n- A valid Gateway token/password for this endpoint should be treated like an owner/operator credential.\n- Requests run through the same control-plane agent path as trusted operator actions.\n- There is no separate non-owner/per-user tool boundary on this endpoint; once a caller passes Gateway auth here, OpenClaw treats that caller as a trusted operator for this gateway.\n- For shared-secret auth modes (`token` and `password`), the endpoint restores the normal full operator defaults even if the caller sends a narrower `x-openclaw-scopes` header.\n- Trusted identity-bearing HTTP modes (for example trusted proxy auth or `gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"`) honor `x-openclaw-scopes` when present and otherwise fall back to the normal operator default scope set.\n- If the target agent policy allows sensitive tools, this endpoint can use them.\n- Keep this endpoint on loopback/tailnet/private ingress only; do not expose it directly to the public internet.\n\nAuth matrix:\n\n- `gateway.auth.mode=\"token\"` or `\"password\"` + `Authorization: Bearer ***`\n  - proves possession of the shared gateway operator secret\n  - ignores narrower `x-openclaw-scopes`\n  - restores the full default operator scope set:\n    `operator.admin`, `operator.approvals`, `operator.pairing`,\n    `operator.read`, `operator.talk.secrets`, `operator.write`\n  - treats chat turns on this endpoint as owner-sender turns\n- trusted identity-bearing HTTP modes (for example trusted proxy auth, or `gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"` on private ingress)\n  - authenticate some outer trusted identity or deployment boundary\n  - honor `x-openclaw-scopes` when the header is present\n  - fall back to the normal operator default scope set when the header is absent\n  - only lose owner semantics when the caller explicitly narrows scopes and omits `operator.admin`\n\nSee [Security](/gateway/security) and [Remote access](/gateway/remote).\n\n## Agent-first model contract\n\nOpenClaw treats the OpenAI `model` field as an **agent target**, not a raw provider model id."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":10,"aggregated":"---\nsummary: \"Expose an OpenAI-compatible /v1/chat/completions HTTP endpoint from the Gateway\"\nread_when:\n  - Integrating tools that expect OpenAI Chat Completions\ntitle: \"OpenAI chat completions\"\n---\n\nOpenClaw’s Gateway can serve a small OpenAI-compatible Chat Completions endpoint.\n\nThis endpoint is **disabled by default**. Enable it in config first.\n\n- `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n- Same port as the Gateway (WS + HTTP multiplex): `http://<gateway-host>:<port>/v1/chat/completions`\n\nWhen the Gateway’s OpenAI-compatible HTTP surface is enabled, it also serves:\n\n- `GET /v1/models`\n- `GET /v1/models/{id}`\n- `POST /v1/embeddings`\n- `POST /v1/responses`\n\nUnder the hood, requests are executed as a normal Gateway agent run (same codepath as `openclaw agent`), so routing/permissions/config match your Gateway.\n\n## Authentication\n\nUses the Gateway auth configuration.\n\nCommon HTTP auth paths:\n\n- shared-secret auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"token\"` or `\"password\"`):\n  `Authorization: Bearer <token-or-password>`\n- trusted identity-bearing HTTP auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"trusted-proxy\"`):\n  route through the configured identity-aware proxy and let it inject the\n  required identity headers\n- private-ingress open auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"`):\n  no auth header required\n\nNotes:\n\n- When `gateway.auth.mode=\"token\"`, use `gateway.auth.token` (or `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN`).\n- When `gateway.auth.mode=\"password\"`, use `gateway.auth.password` (or `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_PASSWORD`).\n- When `gateway.auth.mode=\"trusted-proxy\"`, the HTTP request must come from a\n  configured trusted proxy source; same-host loopback proxies require explicit\n  `gateway.auth.trustedProxy.allowLoopback = true`.\n- If `gateway.auth.rateLimit` is configured and too many auth failures occur, the endpoint returns `429` with `Retry-After`.\n\n## Security boundary (important)\n\nTreat this endpoint as a **full operator-access** surface for the gateway instance.\n\n- HTTP bearer auth here is not a narrow per-user scope model.\n- A valid Gateway token/password for this endpoint should be treated like an owner/operator credential.\n- Requests run through the same control-plane agent path as trusted operator actions.\n- There is no separate non-owner/per-user tool boundary on this endpoint; once a caller passes Gateway auth here, OpenClaw treats that caller as a trusted operator for this gateway.\n- For shared-secret auth modes (`token` and `password`), the endpoint restores the normal full operator defaults even if the caller sends a narrower `x-openclaw-scopes` header.\n- Trusted identity-bearing HTTP modes (for example trusted proxy auth or `gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"`) honor `x-openclaw-scopes` when present and otherwise fall back to the normal operator default scope set.\n- If the target agent policy allows sensitive tools, this endpoint can use them.\n- Keep this endpoint on loopback/tailnet/private ingress only; do not expose it directly to the public internet.\n\nAuth matrix:\n\n- `gateway.auth.mode=\"token\"` or `\"password\"` + `Authorization: Bearer ...`\n  - proves possession of the shared gateway operator secret\n  - ignores narrower `x-openclaw-scopes`\n  - restores the full default operator scope set:\n    `operator.admin`, `operator.approvals`, `operator.pairing`,\n    `operator.read`, `operator.talk.secrets`, `operator.write`\n  - treats chat turns on this endpoint as owner-sender turns\n- trusted identity-bearing HTTP modes (for example trusted proxy auth, or `gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"` on private ingress)\n  - authenticate some outer trusted identity or deployment boundary\n  - honor `x-openclaw-scopes` when the header is present\n  - fall back to the normal operator default scope set when the header is absent\n  - only lose owner semantics when the caller explicitly narrows scopes and omits `operator.admin`\n\nSee [Security](/gateway/security) and [Remote access](/gateway/remote).\n\n## Agent-first model contract\n\nOpenClaw treats the OpenAI `model` field as an **agent target**, not a raw provider model id.","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777667305238}}
{"type":"message","id":"f7e85ba4","parentId":"50104b8e","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:28:27.477Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The OpenAI-compatible endpoint is **disabled by default**. I need to enable it in the config. Let me check the config to see if there's an option for this.\n\nBut wait - I don't want to mess with the gateway config. Let me think of another approach.\n\nActually, looking at the mission-control server, it proxies requests to the gateway on port 18789 with the token. But the endpoint path might not be `/v1/chat/completions`.\n\nLet me look at the gateway config schema to understand how to enable the OpenAI HTTP endpoint.","thinkingSignature":"2626569d1d220377d656880408796463bc7fb1991a463afd092b3940dd7d6687"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_h2oe5axxki2i_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"openaiHttp\\|httpApi\\|/v1/chat\" /opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/ 2>/dev/null | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":987,"output":176,"cacheRead":106688,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":107851,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777667305242,"responseId":"06443fe9e93de021dfa019d99be4d6f5"}}
{"type":"message","id":"3fa8131b","parentId":"f7e85ba4","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:28:27.554Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_h2oe5axxki2i_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-tools.md:    - `models.providers.*.api`: request adapter (`openai-completions`, `openai-responses`, `anthropic-messages`, `google-generative-ai`, etc). For self-hosted `/v1/chat/completions` backends such as MLX, vLLM, SGLang, and most OpenAI-compatible local servers, use `openai-completions`. A custom provider with `baseUrl` but no `api` defaults to `openai-completions`; set `openai-responses` only when the backend supports `/v1/responses`.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/local-models.md:gateways work if they expose an OpenAI-style `/v1/chat/completions`\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/local-models.md:- Direct tiny `/v1/chat/completions` calls work, but `openclaw infer model run --local`\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:summary: \"Expose an OpenAI-compatible /v1/chat/completions HTTP endpoint from the Gateway\"\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:- `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:- Same port as the Gateway (WS + HTTP multiplex): `http://<gateway-host>:<port>/v1/chat/completions`\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:- Existing OpenAI chat clients can usually start with `/v1/chat/completions`.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:curl -sS http://127.0.0.1:18789/v1/chat/completions \\\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:curl -N http://127.0.0.1:18789/v1/chat/completions \\\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:- tiny direct `/v1/chat/completions` calls work"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":38,"aggregated":"/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-tools.md:    - `models.providers.*.api`: request adapter (`openai-completions`, `openai-responses`, `anthropic-messages`, `google-generative-ai`, etc). For self-hosted `/v1/chat/completions` backends such as MLX, vLLM, SGLang, and most OpenAI-compatible local servers, use `openai-completions`. A custom provider with `baseUrl` but no `api` defaults to `openai-completions`; set `openai-responses` only when the backend supports `/v1/responses`.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/local-models.md:gateways work if they expose an OpenAI-style `/v1/chat/completions`\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/local-models.md:- Direct tiny `/v1/chat/completions` calls work, but `openclaw infer model run --local`\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:summary: \"Expose an OpenAI-compatible /v1/chat/completions HTTP endpoint from the Gateway\"\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:- `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:- Same port as the Gateway (WS + HTTP multiplex): `http://<gateway-host>:<port>/v1/chat/completions`\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:- Existing OpenAI chat clients can usually start with `/v1/chat/completions`.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:curl -sS http://127.0.0.1:18789/v1/chat/completions \\\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md:curl -N http://127.0.0.1:18789/v1/chat/completions \\\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:- tiny direct `/v1/chat/completions` calls work","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777667307554}}
{"type":"message","id":"3540b828","parentId":"3fa8131b","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:28:31.080Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The docs show that `POST /v1/chat/completions` should be on the gateway port directly. Let me look at the config to see if the OpenAI HTTP API is enabled.","thinkingSignature":"92326ccf9732092ea3d34d6fc4f7e9c908aceb88b313bf39b462b8ee1b289bb0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3rtiua8nhmm5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openai-http-api.md | grep -A5 \"enable\\|disabled\\|default\\|config\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":582,"output":95,"cacheRead":107648,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":108325,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777667307558,"responseId":"06443feba84f651c2cf9572107ce6b61"}}
{"type":"message","id":"d5064e4a","parentId":"3540b828","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:28:31.164Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_3rtiua8nhmm5_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This endpoint is **disabled by default**. Enable it in config first.\n\n- `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n- Same port as the Gateway (WS + HTTP multiplex): `http://<gateway-host>:<port>/v1/chat/completions`\n\nWhen the Gateway’s OpenAI-compatible HTTP surface is enabled, it also serves:\n\n- `GET /v1/models`\n- `GET /v1/models/{id}`\n- `POST /v1/embeddings`\n- `POST /v1/responses`\n--\nUnder the hood, requests are executed as a normal Gateway agent run (same codepath as `openclaw agent`), so routing/permissions/config match your Gateway.\n\n## Authentication\n\nUses the Gateway auth configuration.\n\nCommon HTTP auth paths:\n\n- shared-secret auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"token\"` or `\"password\"`):\n  `Authorization: Bearer <token-or-password>`\n--\n  route through the configured identity-aware proxy and let it inject the\n  required identity headers\n- private-ingress open auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"`):\n  no auth header required\n\nNotes:\n--\n  configured trusted proxy source; same-host loopback proxies require explicit\n  `gateway.auth.trustedProxy.allowLoopback = true`.\n- If `gateway.auth.rateLimit` is configured and too many auth failures occur, the endpoint returns `429` with `Retry-After`.\n\n## Security boundary (important)\n\nTreat this endpoint as a **full operator-access** surface for the gateway instance.\n\n--\n- For shared-secret auth modes (`token` and `password`), the endpoint restores the normal full operator defaults even if the caller sends a narrower `x-openclaw-scopes` header.\n- Trusted identity-bearing HTTP modes (for example trusted proxy auth or `gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"`) honor `x-openclaw-scopes` when present and otherwise fall back to the normal operator default scope set.\n- If the target agent policy allows sensitive tools, this endpoint can use them.\n- Keep this endpoint on loopback/tailnet/private ingress only; do not expose it directly to the public internet.\n\nAuth matrix:\n\n--\n  - restores the full default operator scope set:\n    `operator.admin`, `operator.approvals`, `operator.pairing`,\n    `operator.read`, `operator.talk.secrets`, `operator.write`\n  - treats chat turns on this endpoint as owner-sender turns\n- trusted identity-bearing HTTP modes (for example trusted proxy auth, or `gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"` on private ingress)\n  - authenticate some outer trusted identity or deployment boundary\n--\n  - fall back to the normal operator default scope set when the header is absent\n  - only lose owner semantics when the caller explicitly narrows scopes and omits `operator.admin`\n\nSee [Security](/gateway/security) and [Remote access](/gateway/remote).\n\n## Agent-first model contract\n--\n- `model: \"openclaw\"` routes to the configured default agent.\n- `model: \"openclaw/default\"` also routes to the configured default agent.\n- `model: \"openclaw/<agentId>\"` routes to a specific agent.\n\nOptional request headers:\n\n- `x-openclaw-model: <provider/model-or-bare-id>` overrides the backend model for the selected agent.\n--\nSet `gateway.http.endpoints.chatCompletions.enabled` to `true`:\n\n```json5\n{\n  gateway: {\n    http: {\n--\n        chatCompletions: { enabled: true },\n      },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n--\nSet `gateway.http.endpoints.chatCompletions.enabled` to `false`:\n\n```json5\n{\n  gateway: {\n    http: {\n--\n        chatCompletions: { enabled: false },\n      },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n--\nBy default the endpoint is **stateless per request** (a new session key is generated each call).\n\nIf the request includes an OpenAI `user` string, the Gateway derives a stable session key from it, so repeated calls can share an agent session.\n\n## Why this surface matters\n\n--\n    The returned ids are `openclaw`, `openclaw/default`, and `openclaw/<agentId>` entries.\n    Use them directly as OpenAI `model` values.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"Does `/v1/models` list agents or sub-agents?\">\n    It lists top-level agent targets, not backend provider models and not sub-agents.\n--\n  <Accordion title=\"Why is `openclaw/default` included?\">\n    `openclaw/default` is the stable alias for the configured default agent.\n\n    That means clients can keep using one predictable id even if the real default agent id changes between environments.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"How do I override the backend model?\">\n    Use `x-openclaw-model`.\n\n--\n    If you omit it, the selected agent runs with its normal configured model choice.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"How do embeddings fit this contract?\">\n    `/v1/embeddings` uses the same agent-target `model` ids.\n\n    Use `model: \"openclaw/default\"` or `model: \"openclaw/<agentId>\"`.\n    When you need a specific embedding model, send it in `x-openclaw-model`.\n    Without that header, the request passes through to the selected agent's normal embedding setup.\n\n  </Accordion>\n</AccordionGroup>\n--\n- Model: `openclaw/default`\n\nExpected behavior:\n\n- `GET /v1/models` should list `openclaw/default`\n- Open WebUI should use `openclaw/default` as the chat model id\n- If you want a specific backend provider/model for that agent, set the agent's normal default model or send `x-openclaw-model`\n\nQuick smoke:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sS http://127.0.0.1:18789/v1/models \\\n--\nIf that returns `openclaw/default`, most Open WebUI setups can connect with the same base URL and token.\n\n## Examples\n\nNon-streaming:\n\n--\n    \"model\": \"openclaw/default\",\n    \"messages\": [{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"}]\n  }'\n```\n\nStreaming:\n--\ncurl -sS http://127.0.0.1:18789/v1/models/openclaw%2Fdefault \\\n  -H 'Authorization: Bearer ***'\n```\n\nCreate embeddings:\n\n--\n    \"model\": \"openclaw/default\",\n    \"input\": [\"alpha\", \"beta\"]\n  }'\n```\n\nNotes:\n--\n- `openclaw/default` is always present so one stable id works across environments.\n- Backend provider/model overrides belong in `x-openclaw-model`, not the OpenAI `model` field.\n- `/v1/embeddings` supports `input` as a string or array of strings.\n\n## Related\n\n- [Configuration reference](/gateway/configuration-reference)\n- [OpenAI](/providers/openai)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":14,"aggregated":"This endpoint is **disabled by default**. Enable it in config first.\n\n- `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n- Same port as the Gateway (WS + HTTP multiplex): `http://<gateway-host>:<port>/v1/chat/completions`\n\nWhen the Gateway’s OpenAI-compatible HTTP surface is enabled, it also serves:\n\n- `GET /v1/models`\n- `GET /v1/models/{id}`\n- `POST /v1/embeddings`\n- `POST /v1/responses`\n--\nUnder the hood, requests are executed as a normal Gateway agent run (same codepath as `openclaw agent`), so routing/permissions/config match your Gateway.\n\n## Authentication\n\nUses the Gateway auth configuration.\n\nCommon HTTP auth paths:\n\n- shared-secret auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"token\"` or `\"password\"`):\n  `Authorization: Bearer <token-or-password>`\n--\n  route through the configured identity-aware proxy and let it inject the\n  required identity headers\n- private-ingress open auth (`gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"`):\n  no auth header required\n\nNotes:\n--\n  configured trusted proxy source; same-host loopback proxies require explicit\n  `gateway.auth.trustedProxy.allowLoopback = true`.\n- If `gateway.auth.rateLimit` is configured and too many auth failures occur, the endpoint returns `429` with `Retry-After`.\n\n## Security boundary (important)\n\nTreat this endpoint as a **full operator-access** surface for the gateway instance.\n\n--\n- For shared-secret auth modes (`token` and `password`), the endpoint restores the normal full operator defaults even if the caller sends a narrower `x-openclaw-scopes` header.\n- Trusted identity-bearing HTTP modes (for example trusted proxy auth or `gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"`) honor `x-openclaw-scopes` when present and otherwise fall back to the normal operator default scope set.\n- If the target agent policy allows sensitive tools, this endpoint can use them.\n- Keep this endpoint on loopback/tailnet/private ingress only; do not expose it directly to the public internet.\n\nAuth matrix:\n\n--\n  - restores the full default operator scope set:\n    `operator.admin`, `operator.approvals`, `operator.pairing`,\n    `operator.read`, `operator.talk.secrets`, `operator.write`\n  - treats chat turns on this endpoint as owner-sender turns\n- trusted identity-bearing HTTP modes (for example trusted proxy auth, or `gateway.auth.mode=\"none\"` on private ingress)\n  - authenticate some outer trusted identity or deployment boundary\n--\n  - fall back to the normal operator default scope set when the header is absent\n  - only lose owner semantics when the caller explicitly narrows scopes and omits `operator.admin`\n\nSee [Security](/gateway/security) and [Remote access](/gateway/remote).\n\n## Agent-first model contract\n--\n- `model: \"openclaw\"` routes to the configured default agent.\n- `model: \"openclaw/default\"` also routes to the configured default agent.\n- `model: \"openclaw/<agentId>\"` routes to a specific agent.\n\nOptional request headers:\n\n- `x-openclaw-model: <provider/model-or-bare-id>` overrides the backend model for the selected agent.\n--\nSet `gateway.http.endpoints.chatCompletions.enabled` to `true`:\n\n```json5\n{\n  gateway: {\n    http: {\n--\n        chatCompletions: { enabled: true },\n      },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n--\nSet `gateway.http.endpoints.chatCompletions.enabled` to `false`:\n\n```json5\n{\n  gateway: {\n    http: {\n--\n        chatCompletions: { enabled: false },\n      },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n--\nBy default the endpoint is **stateless per request** (a new session key is generated each call).\n\nIf the request includes an OpenAI `user` string, the Gateway derives a stable session key from it, so repeated calls can share an agent session.\n\n## Why this surface matters\n\n--\n    The returned ids are `openclaw`, `openclaw/default`, and `openclaw/<agentId>` entries.\n    Use them directly as OpenAI `model` values.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"Does `/v1/models` list agents or sub-agents?\">\n    It lists top-level agent targets, not backend provider models and not sub-agents.\n--\n  <Accordion title=\"Why is `openclaw/default` included?\">\n    `openclaw/default` is the stable alias for the configured default agent.\n\n    That means clients can keep using one predictable id even if the real default agent id changes between environments.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"How do I override the backend model?\">\n    Use `x-openclaw-model`.\n\n--\n    If you omit it, the selected agent runs with its normal configured model choice.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"How do embeddings fit this contract?\">\n    `/v1/embeddings` uses the same agent-target `model` ids.\n\n    Use `model: \"openclaw/default\"` or `model: \"openclaw/<agentId>\"`.\n    When you need a specific embedding model, send it in `x-openclaw-model`.\n    Without that header, the request passes through to the selected agent's normal embedding setup.\n\n  </Accordion>\n</AccordionGroup>\n--\n- Model: `openclaw/default`\n\nExpected behavior:\n\n- `GET /v1/models` should list `openclaw/default`\n- Open WebUI should use `openclaw/default` as the chat model id\n- If you want a specific backend provider/model for that agent, set the agent's normal default model or send `x-openclaw-model`\n\nQuick smoke:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sS http://127.0.0.1:18789/v1/models \\\n--\nIf that returns `openclaw/default`, most Open WebUI setups can connect with the same base URL and token.\n\n## Examples\n\nNon-streaming:\n\n--\n    \"model\": \"openclaw/default\",\n    \"messages\": [{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi\"}]\n  }'\n```\n\nStreaming:\n--\ncurl -sS http://127.0.0.1:18789/v1/models/openclaw%2Fdefault \\\n  -H 'Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN'\n```\n\nCreate embeddings:\n\n--\n    \"model\": \"openclaw/default\",\n    \"input\": [\"alpha\", \"beta\"]\n  }'\n```\n\nNotes:\n--\n- `openclaw/default` is always present so one stable id works across environments.\n- Backend provider/model overrides belong in `x-openclaw-model`, not the OpenAI `model` field.\n- `/v1/embeddings` supports `input` as a string or array of strings.\n\n## Related\n\n- [Configuration reference](/gateway/configuration-reference)\n- [OpenAI](/providers/openai)","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777667311163}}
