{"type":"message","id":"d24e3eef","parentId":"4ace4fb4","timestamp":"2026-05-01T23:22:56.964Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_9frmgr526yk4_1","toolName":"process","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[00:00.000 --> 00:06.840]  okay so basically how I want it to work is kind of like a walkie-talkie I hold\n[00:06.840 --> 00:11.760]  down the button and I speak and then when I let go you reply to me with your\n[00:11.760 --> 00:19.000]  response using the system default voice the non specified voice are there any\n[00:19.000 --> 00:23.760]  other questions that you have to clarify this for you\nokay so basically how I want it to work is kind of like a walkie-talkie I hold\ndown the button and I speak and then when I let go you reply to me with your\nresponse using the system default voice the non specified voice are there any\nother questions that you have to clarify this for you\n\nProcess exited with code 0."}],"details":{"status":"completed","sessionId":"good-dune","exitCode":0,"aggregated":"[00:00.000 --> 00:06.840]  okay so basically how I want it to work is kind of like a walkie-talkie I hold\n[00:06.840 --> 00:11.760]  down the button and I speak and then when I let go you reply to me with your\n[00:11.760 --> 00:19.000]  response using the system default voice the non specified voice are there any\n[00:19.000 --> 00:23.760]  other questions that you have to clarify this for you\nokay so basically how I want it to work is kind of like a walkie-talkie I hold\ndown the button and I speak and then when I let go you reply to me with your\nresponse using the system default voice the non specified voice are there any\nother questions that you have to clarify this for you\n","name":"# Transcribe"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777677776964}}
{"type":"message","id":"fa03307e","parentId":"d24e3eef","timestamp":"2026-05-01T23:23:05.317Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Bobby's voice memo clarifies exactly what he wants:\n\n1. **Walkie-talkie style** - hold button, speak, release, Dean replies\n2. **System default voice** - not a specified voice, just the default system voice\n3. He doesn't have other questions - he wants to know if I have questions to clarify\n\nSo he basically wants:\n- Push-to-talk (like a walkie-talkie) ✓ (already implemented)\n- When he lets go, Dean responds with voice ✓ (already implemented)\n- System default voice (not a specific Siri/Alexa voice) ✓ (already using system `say` command)\n\nThe core experience he wants IS what I built. The problem is purely technical reliability - the audio playback keeps failing on iPhone.\n\nLet me think about what's actually failing:\n1. Audio recording on iPhone Safari - seems to work (we got \"Hello Dean how are you\" transcribed)\n2. Transcription - works ✓\n3. AI response - works ✓  \n4. Audio file generation - works ✓\n5. Audio playback on iPhone - FAILS with \"connection error\"\n\nThe issue is the proxy on port 8790 isn't reliably serving the audio files to the iPhone over Tailscale. The audio files are being generated correctly, but the iPhone can't fetch them.\n\nActually wait - there's another issue. The proxy is proxying requests to port 8791, but when the iPhone tries to load `http://localhost:8790/audio/reply.mp3` via the proxy, it needs to serve the static file. Let me check if the `/audio/` route in the proxy is actually working.\n\nActually the audio files are on the local filesystem at `/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/Telephone/audio/`. The proxy at port 8790 serves static files from the Telephone directory. So `/audio/reply_xxx.mp3` should map to `/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/Telephone/audio/reply_xxx.mp3`.\n\n\nI need to verify the proxy's audio route is actually working—maybe the issue is that Safari is trying to fetch the audio file before it's fully written, or there's a CORS issue preventing playback. Since the audio generation happens after the AI response, there's a timing gap where the file might not be ready when the iPhone requests it. The proxy itself should be capable of serving static files directly from the filesystem, so the problem might be something else entirely. The issue might be that the audio element in telephone.html is trying to fetch from a localhost URL that the iPhone can't reach since it's making requests to `http://localhost:8790` from the phone, but localhost there refers to the phone itself, not the Mac. The proxy needs to serve the audio file directly at that endpoint so the iPhone can actually retrieve it.","thinkingSignature":"d542d1384aece9f23c395b75b92d7b7ac7877c84324193e99dc98b3f5de5bc48"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nGot it! That's exactly what we built — walkie-talkie style, hold to talk, release to hear Dean respond. The issue is purely technical reliability with serving audio to your iPhone.\n\nOne clarifying question: **you want the system default voice (the Mac TTS voice), which is what we're already using.** So that part is right.\n\nThe real question is why audio playback keeps failing on your iPhone. Let me check one thing:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9auzgz4vp33e_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Test if audio is reachable from \"external\" perspective\n# The proxy serves /audio/ files - let's verify it works\nls -la ~/Desktop/Telephone/audio/*.mp3 | tail -3\n\n# Test the audio endpoint\nRECENT=$(ls -t ~/Desktop/Telephone/audio/*.mp3 | head -1)\ncurl -s --max-time 3 \"http://localhost:8790/audio/$(basename $RECENT)\" | head -c 100 | xxd | head -3\necho \"File exists and is $(wc -c < $RECENT) bytes\"\n\n# Check the proxy log for errors\ntail -10 ~/.openclaw/logs/telephone-http.log 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":281,"output":839,"cacheRead":102080,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":103200,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777677776967,"responseId":"064468d1068d2bf2e95cf9be9413b24d"}}
